In C there are basically two ‚Äúnormal‚Äù ways to stop execution and return control (and a status code) back to the operating system, plus a few variants for abnormal termination:

1. Returning from main()  
   ‚Ä¢ If you‚Äôre in  
     ```c
     int main(void) { ‚Ä¶ }
     ```  
     then  
     ```c
     return 0;      // success
     return 1;      // non-zero indicates error
     ```  
     will terminate the program, run all cleanup for local objects in main, flush stdio streams, invoke any atexit() handlers, and finally hand control back to the OS.  
   ‚Ä¢ If you just fall off the end of main (i.e. run past the closing brace), C99 and later assume `return 0;`.

2. Calling exit() (from <stdlib.h>)  
   ```c
   #include <stdlib.h>
   ‚Ä¶  
   exit(0);        // like return 0 from main
   exit(1);        // non‚Äêzero = error
   ```  
   What exit() does:  
   ‚Äì Flushes and closes all open stdio streams  
   ‚Äì Calls all functions registered with atexit()  
   ‚Äì Returns your status code to the OS  

Abnormal/Immediate termination variants  
‚Äì abort()  (in <stdlib.h>)  
  ‚Ä¢ Causes abnormal program termination  
  ‚Ä¢ No cleanup of stdio streams, no atexit() calls  
  ‚Ä¢ Typically causes a core-dump or crash report  

‚Äì _Exit(status)  (in C99, <stdlib.h>)  
  ‚Ä¢ Terminate immediately with the given status  
  ‚Ä¢ No flushing of stdio, no atexit() calls  

‚Äì quick_exit(status)  (in C11, <stdlib.h>)  
  ‚Ä¢ A ‚Äúlighter‚Äù exit that runs handlers registered by at_quick_exit() but won‚Äôt flush stdio or do full cleanup  

‚Äì Signals:  
  You can also raise or send a signal to yourself to terminate  
  ```c
  #include <signal.h>
  raise(SIGTERM);
  ```
  This invokes whatever signal handler is installed (default is to terminate).

Example showing the common methods:  
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <signal.h>

void goodbye(void) {
    puts("Goodbye, world!");
}

int main(void) {
    atexit(goodbye);      // register a handler

    puts("Hello!");

    if (/* some error */ 0) {
        // abnormal termination:
        abort();
    }

    // normal termination:
    // either:
    //   return 0;
    // or:
    exit(0);

    // or (no cleanup at all):
    // _Exit(0);

    // or send yourself a signal:
    // raise(SIGTERM);
}
```

Key points  
‚Ä¢ `return` from `main()` and `exit()` are the standard, graceful ways: they do full cleanup and report status.  
‚Ä¢ `abort()` and `_Exit()`/`quick_exit()` skip cleanup and are used for emergency terminations.  
‚Ä¢ The integer you pass back (0 versus non‚Äêzero) is your program‚Äôs ‚Äúexit code‚Äù and can be queried by scripts or parent processes.

